rComments: Professor Cunningham's approach to anthropology is incredibly refreshing. She utilizes a variety of different sources, including short stories and film. She will teach you to think outside the box and to critically any taken for granted assumptions you may have about what concepts like nature and culture.

I took this course in 2013 and it was one of the best courses I took in first year. You will be required to do a lot of reading, but the material is very easy to get through (a lot of short stories and other engaging sources). As long as you do the readings, the tests are a breeze.

Professor Cunningham is a great prof, one of the best in the department. She expects a certain degree of prior knowledge, which is expected by 3rd year. This is my second class with her and I recommend her to students who are truly want to learn and open their minds. I agree with the reviewers below about the lack of "spoon-feeding", great IMO!

Great prof! This was one of the best classes I have taken at U of T. Take her class if you want to critically engage with material and open your mind to alternate ways of thinking. Her quizzes force you to do your reading and prepare you for the final assignment. If you like being spoon-fed, don't take her class.
Professor Cunningham is a unique and great teacher. She is knowledgeable and approaches things in her own way, something you will notice on day 1.

Professor Cunningham's class was a real treat. Her teaching style may not be for everyone, but I found it to be original and inspiring. She will make you consider you never though of and put a different spin on things you already know.

I'm also really surprised by the negative reviews. In my experience, Cunningham was supportive, approachable, and made class a fun experience. I feel like the below reviewer expects a professor with the "show up and spoon feed the students" mentality. Don't take her course if you want an easy A, take her course to learn a lot and be rewarded.

I have never met anyone more confused in my life. I took this class as first year seminar because it seemed interesting. She is very self absorbed (spent an entire class telling us how crazy her neighbour is) and was very unclear with assignments.  Very weird lady overall. She did bring us cookies which was nice.

i agree with below review. this is a cool course because NO textbook yay! class uses all kinds of material like movies, pictures, short stories, poems, etc. Also for a big class there is a lot of discussion. prof and TA are both helpful. the concepts are confusing though, but i'm learning a lot.

I'm an upper-year student taking ANT110. this is a very difficult for a first-year course, but the Prof makes it more fun with movies and literature. Her class is rare at u of t for using different types of material and being very open for discussion. If you think the stuff in this course is "weird," maybe you should expand your horizons !
She is a good prof, her classes are pretty weird tho, pretty confusing stuff...

Please keep in mind that 1st year students rating within 1 week of 1st class is not reliable. Prof. has worked to develop critical thinking skills, including discussions prior to tests. Great intro to Cultural Anthro; if you can see Nature differently (as promised) you can see anything differently. Very caring, although a little confusing at times

Lost me on the first day of class. Lectures are boring, professor is self-important, not to mention one of the most annoying speakers I've ever met (her way of speaking is just...if you've ever had her, you'll know what I mean), material is practically useless -- nothing you can't learn by yourself.

Not helpful at all. I was semi-excited for this class, but found upon the first lecture that it was a huge waste of time. It made me want to drop right away - Prof. tends to talk a lot about herself (reviews here are true), class felt like elementary school: all we do is watch films and compare pictures of lawns. Don't waste your time on it.
No Comments
Course material was redundant but interesting. Overall, Prof Cunningham was great yet her marking was a bit inconsistent.

extremely inconsistent. Talked the entire time about "community" and gave easy assignments. Then gave the most confusing tests ever and no one knows how she marks papers. The material is easy, but the grading and tests without any time screw you over

Professor Cunningham is a passionate and enthusiastic teacher.  She loves to invoke independent thoughts from her students and shows genuine interest in their ideas.  Very flexible to meet students' needs.  A little funny too!
What is a learning cell? Maybe a past learning cell for us to see, with a good mark, might help.
Excellent Professor - Really cares about her students - also is brilliant!!1

VERY condescending. example: "When I did my PhD at YALE..."...paused for a reaction... too caught up in her feministic views to properly teach. Made us unecessarily spend a lot of money on books we never used.

The textbooks she assigned for this class were very expensive, did not relate to the course content, and was not at the introductory level as per the course description. She spoke in a condescending and pretentious manner that made the lectures unbearable
"Cunning"ham - point made.
I mean cammon.. her name says it all "Cunningham".
The textbooks for this course are old, outdated, expensive and not useful. It made me want to switch my major.

She's an ok prof. Too condescending, boring, showed too many videos, wasn't clear in her lecture material, not organized AT ALL. Avoid her at all costs!! Very feminist (nothing wrong with that, but concentrate on ANTHRO please). BORING. Midterm = Easy

Very Flakey: every anthro class, it was like a blizzard of her up there.  She made up words and was condescending.  A lot of talk about feminism and genetics, but very little about culture (both our own and other peoples)

This prof is clueless to the fact that she's not teaching her students anything. Maybe if she played more videos and talked less, her classes would become a little more interesting. Making us buy 3 books for 1/4 of the course is just ludicrous!

Sometimes I couldn't tell whether it was a medical anthro lecture on genetics with too much crap about metaphor thrown in, or a semiotic anthro lecture about metaphor with too much background about genetics thrown in. And what the hell is  listen-watch &#

If I ever hear 'vis-a-vis' 'problematize' or 'I did my Ph.d at yale' again, I am going to kill myself.  Lectures incredibly boring.  Idea of buying 3 textbooks for a quarter of the year absolutely ridiculous.  More annoying than anyone I have ever met.

Passionate about what she does, very approachable and a good lecturer. But forcing students to buy 3 UPPER year DENSE textbooks for 5 classes (at $130!) is ridiculous! Lectures have nothing to do with texts or tutorials & all are above an ANT100 level.
My complaints:  we had to buy $125 worth of books for a quarter of a course!  Most people will never take another anthro course, but she inists we will need these books for years to come.
Can you say pretentious? She can! She's scattered, unhelpfull, and deliberately condecending. Not a good teacher or person.
tends to assume that students have a massive background in anthro theory WHEN THEY DO NOT.  if she says 'vis-a-vis' one more time I am going to shoot myself.  she is nice though.
